Negative Interest Rate Club
Brussels - Over much of the past decade, central banks have made only limited progress in curbing strong global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Federal Reserve has kept interest rates at near-zero levels and has also conducted multiple unprecedented balance sheet expansions through large-scale bond purchase programs.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank have also followed the Federal Reserve's lead, implementing their own versions of so-called "quantitative easing" (QE).
But inflation has not received a reasonable increase anywhere.
Although these countries are all fighting deflationary pressures, their monetary policies — and economic performance — are diverging.
The current growth in the US and UK is strong enough to allow them to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the eurozone and Japan are intensifying their QE measures, pushing long-term policy interest rates further into negative territory.
Why is this distinction made?
The short answer is debt.
For decades, the United States and the United Kingdom have had current account deficits, making them debtors, while the euro area and Japan have had current account surpluses, making them creditors.
Negative interest rates benefit debtors rather than creditors, so the negative interest rate policy introduced after the global economic crisis stimulated recovery in the US and the UK, but had little effect on the Eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
So far, most of the world's creditor countries — countries with sustained large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland — have experienced negative interest rates, not only on long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also on medium-term bonds.
This is definitely not a good thing.
Although the effects of low interest rates have been limited, the central banks of these economies have still maintained this policy.
If you argue that quantitative easing or lowering interest rates cannot benefit the economy, they will sidestep the issue and refute the idea that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy — which appears flawless on the surface.
But in reality, it's full of flaws.
Basic economics courses all mention this peculiar phenomenon known as the "backward-bending supply curve of savings": in certain environments, a decrease in interest rates leads to an increase in savings.
Because the decline in interest rates reduces savers' income, they will decrease their spending, especially if they have a goal of saving for retirement.
None of this is to deny the general rule — which forms the basis of modern monetary decisions — that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other spending.
However, the impact varies depending on the different debt situations of the economies.
In a closed economy, each creditor has a debtor, so regardless of what the creditor loses due to extremely low interest rates, the debtor should benefit.
But in an economy with a large net foreign asset position, creditors will naturally be more numerous than debtors.
The situation is exactly the opposite for a country with a large amount of foreign debt.
Therefore, the effects of a lower bound interest rate monetary policy differ between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important, as foreign asset positions were often relatively small (as a percentage of GDP).
However, today, the foreign asset positions of major industrialized economies are substantial and increasingly diversified, in part due to the leverage that contributed to the 2007–2008 global financial crisis.
In fact, at the national level, leverage is still increasing.
Although the current account imbalances have somewhat eased since the start of the financial crisis, they have not been reversed.
This means that surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor positions, creating a divergence with deficit economies.
Some large commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, have substantial current account surpluses when oil prices are high, making them the main exceptions in the diversification of foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, world oil prices have plummeted, reversing the wealth trends of these countries.
Their export revenues plunged sharply — in many countries, by half — forcing them to run deficits, relying on their vast sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodities boom.
Now, a significant reduction in spending is inevitable.
Industrialized economies face entirely different challenges.
Their problem—somewhat speaking, a question of luxury—is ensuring that consumers spend the windfall they gain from the drop in import prices.
However, in creditor countries, negative interest rates seem not to be advancing this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This division also exists within the eurozone.
Although, as a whole, the eurozone is a creditor economy, there are also debt countries within it.
Debt-driven economies, such as Spain and Portugal, now have frequently recurring current account surpluses and are gradually reducing their debt.
However, the current account surpluses of traditional debtor countries are too high, leading to the continued increase in the debtor/country asymmetry.
Most notably, since the outbreak of the financial crisis, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, meaning that the surplus accumulated during this period exceeds the total surplus accumulated in previous years.
Following the current trend, German claims may rise from 60% to 100% of GDP.
The central bank governor should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend of central bank independence precisely because central bank governors are less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bank governors seem to have short tempers, struggling greatly with low inflation, even though the output gap is gradually closing and both the U.S. and Japan have achieved full employment.
The central bank governor of the debtor country must stop manipulating the economy through further monetary easing that could be detrimental to production.
In contrast, they should allow the recovery to develop on its own, even if it is very slow, and wait for the base effect of falling oil prices to disappear.
European Central Bank President Draghi recently acknowledged that, in today's global environment, the current monetary policy stance may not be effective.
But promising more is not the solution.
